ality that repressing it easily risks harming vulnerable people and communities. Charting the efforts of both the judiciary and a citizen's social movement to reverse the mafia's economic, political, and cultural power, the authors establish a framework for understanding both the difficulties and the accomplishments of Sicily's multifaceted antimafia efforts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMafiazItalyzPalermoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a19th century.  a20th century.  aantimafia.  acity life.  acold war.  acrime boss.  acrime.  acriminals.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  acultural.  aeconomics.  afinancial.  aitalian history.  aitalian mafia.  amafia history.  amafia.  amob boss.  aorganized crime.  apalermo.  aprotests.  areal estate.  asicily.  asocial change.  asocial history.  asocial movement.  asocial studies.  asubculture.  aurban.  aviolence.  awealth.  aworld history.1 aSchneider, Jane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092949440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929494423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929494/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY